title: Phase Iia, Multicenter, Randomized, Third-party Unblinded, Adjuvant And Placebo-controlled, Multiple Ascending Dose, Safety, Tolerability, And Immunogenicity Trial Of Acc-001 And Qs-21 Adjuvant In Subjects With Mild To Moderate Alzheimers Disease
description_brief: To access the safety, tolerability, and immunogenicity of ACC-001, an investigational active immunization, in subjects with mild to moderate Alzheimer's disease.

participantFlowModule.preAssignmentDetails: The Basic Results disclose pooled data from studies NCT00479557 and NCT00498602.
participantFlowModule.recruitmentDetails: Planned duration was approximately 110 weeks (including 6 week screening period, 52 weeks of dosing, and 52 weeks of follow-up). Participants who completed the NCT00498602 study through Week 78 had the option to exit after this time point, for continued treatment and follow-up under extension protocol extension protocol NCT00960531.

measures.title: Mini-Mental State Examination (MMSE) Score
measures.description: The MMSE was used to systematically and thoroughly assess mental status of participants. It is an 11-question measure that tests five areas of cognitive function: orientation, registration, attention and calculation, recall, and language. The total score ranges from 0 to 30. A score of 23 or lower is indicative of cognitive impairment.

outcomeMeasures.title: Percentage of Participants With Treatment-emergent AEs or Serious Adverse Events (SAEs)
outcomeMeasures.description: An AE was any untoward, undesired, or unplanned clinical event in the form of signs, symptoms, disease, or laboratory or physiologic observations occurring in a person given study drug or in a sponsor's clinical study. The event did not need to be causally related to the study drug or the clinical studies. A treatment emergent AE was defined as an event that emerged during the treatment period that was absent before treatment, or worsened during the treatment period relative to the pretreatment state. An SAE was an AE resulting in any of the following outcomes or deemed significant for any other reason: death; initial or prolonged inpatient hospitalization; life-threatening experience (immediate risk of dying); persistent or significant disability/incapacity; congenital anomaly.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: The safety population included all randomized participants with documented use of at least one dose of study drug.

certainAgreement.otherDetails: Pfizer has the right to review disclosures, requesting a delay of less than 60 days. Investigator will postpone single center publications until after disclosure of pooled data (all sites), less than 12 months from study completion/termination at all participating sites. Investigator may not disclose previously undisclosed confidential information other than study results.

drug: ACC-001 (vanutide cridificar) — active immunotherapeutic vaccine targeting the N‑terminal Aβ(1–7) peptide
QS-21 adjuvant (Quillaja saponaria saponin) — adjuvant used with ACC‑001
placebo: QS-21 alone or PBS used as control in some arms
explanation_target: Reason: The trial tests ACC-001 described as an "investigational active immunization" and the full title names ACC-001 with QS-21 adjuvant for mild–moderate AD, indicating a vaccine intended to elicit an immune response against Alzheimer pathology (not a symptomatic cognitive enhancer or neuropsychiatric treatment). citeturn0search7turn0search5

Act: Web search identifies ACC-001 as vanutide cridificar, an anti-amyloid-β vaccine composed of the Aβ N‑terminal (1–7) peptide conjugated to a carrier (CRM197) and given with QS-21 to elicit anti‑Aβ antibodies — i.e., a biologic designed to target amyloid pathology. Key trial reports and phase‑2 publications describe safety, tolerability, and immunogenicity endpoints for ACC‑001 + QS‑21. citeturn0search2turn0search3

Reflect: Given ACC‑001 is an immunotherapeutic vaccine aimed at generating anti‑Aβ antibodies to reduce amyloid burden, the correct category is "disease-targeted biologic." (Not a small molecule, cognitive enhancer, or symptomatic psychiatric treatment.) Note: some phase‑2 results reported no statistically significant reduction in PET amyloid vs placebo despite robust antibody responses, but that does not change the intervention category. citeturn0search1turn0search3
explanation_agent: Reason: The trial tests ACC-001 (vanutide cridificar), an active immunotherapeutic vaccine built from the N‑terminal Aβ(1–7) peptide conjugated to a CRM197 carrier and given with QS‑21 adjuvant to elicit anti‑Aβ antibodies — i.e., it is explicitly designed to target amyloid‑β pathology in Alzheimer disease. citeturn0search0turn0search4

Act: Extracted details — ACC‑001 (vanutide cridificar) = Aβ(1–7) peptide vaccine conjugated to CRM197; QS‑21 = saponin adjuvant used to boost immunogenicity. The trial endpoints (immunogenicity, safety, amyloid PET) and multiple published phase‑2 reports confirm the intervention’s mechanism is anti‑amyloid immunization. Therefore assign CADRO category A) Amyloid beta. citeturn0search2turn0search1

Reflect: The intervention is a disease‑targeted biologic aimed at inducing anti‑Aβ antibodies rather than a symptomatic or non‑therapeutic intervention. No other primary target (e.g., tau, inflammation alone, metabolism) is indicated, so the most specific CADRO match is A) Amyloid beta. Published trial results showing immunogenicity but no significant PET reduction do not change the target classification. citeturn0search3turn0search0
